R1: I judged the appropriateness based on the proximity to other people, the presumption this is some kind of party (music playing), and how much these actions would affect people both physically (moving large objects) and socially (interrupting the gathering).
R2: Seems like the robot is in a position to do housework and carry out more disruptive tasks (cleaning etc.) while people are not near it.
R3: Children in the room, so could be carrying small toys etc to interact with them -- wouldn't be appropriate to stand in this circle just holding food, drinks etc. while people are walking around.
R4: Again seems like a party/gathering. Moving around in this small space to serve food and drinks would be good.
R5: Same as before: providing things that people need in a small area while not carrying out tasks that would be obsctructive.
R6: Close proximity, people clearly waiting to receive something from the robot - cleaning or carrying out other activities would be weird here.
R7: The robot seems to be moving away from people, so carrying out small chores would be sensible -- moving large objects while people are in the room would be a bit strange, and carrying food or drinks away from people wouldn't make sense.
R8: With people gathered, making conversation and serving drinks would be a normal interaction. Carrying around large items would be dangerous, and interrupting a conversation to clean would be annoying.
R9: The path around the robot is clear, so carrying out chores or moving large objects would be acceptable. There's no indication that it needs to make contact with anyone here.
R10: In this zone with little contact with other people, the robot would not look out of place carrying out these chores and would be minimally invasive.
R11: Again, very far away from people so it would be fine to carry out chores.
R12: Another party scene with people mingling - fine to converse or to bring refreshments.
R13: A very quiet room -- good time for carrying out these chores without people nearby.
R14: Clearly zoned with no people nearby: a good time to clean this area.
R15: Someone appears to be sleeping: not appropriate to carry out noisy tasks, but mopping or putting away small objects wouldn't be too bad here if it's quiet.
R16: People routinely passing by, but not blocking off the whole area if the robot needs to get in the way to clean etc.
R17: Mopping the floor by the stairs would be dangerous while the room is busy -- dry cleaning activities would be fine.
R18: People relaxing for the evening. Bringing food or drinks would be okay, but disturbing with chores would not be.
R19: Another party: fine to serve food and drinks, and to clean any spillages, but not okay to carry out big disruptive tasks.
R20: Paths are clear, people far away so bigger tasks such as cleaning and moving large objects poses no danger.

R1: Cleaning a room while it is being used by a group of people is not ideal, particularly when making noise (vacuuming). When engaging in conversation, social protocol dictates that the initiator should face the intended recipient.
R2: Noisy cleaning in the presence of others should be avoided. When staying a conversation, the initiator should face the recipient and be within reasonable proximity.
R3: Mopping or vacuuming right next to other people should be avoided, as should carrying large or hot items that might present a danger to others.
R4: Noisy cleaning should not be performed in the vicinity of others. Mopping or carrying hit or large items could represent a danger to others, so should generally be avoided in close proximity to others.
R5: Noisy cleaning in a populated room should be avoided. Carrying large or hot items, or mopping, in close proximity to others should generally be avoided as it could endanger others.
R6: The robot appears to be within the personal space of at least one other person. That should in itself be avoided and very few actions are socially acceptable that close to others.
R7: Proximity to others limits what potentially dangerous or noisy actions are socially reasonable. Starting a conversation requires facing the intended recipient.
R8: Very close proximity to others severely limits the actions that are reasonable. Even serving drinks or food should be done at a reasonable distance if possible and not in the middle of a crowd.
R9: Noisy cleaning, or cleaning that leaves the floor wet, should not be done in an occupied room.
R10: Noisy or disruptive actions should not be performed in an occupied room. Large objects should not be carried in proximity to others and care should be taken when carrying hot food in proximity to others, but could be acceptable depending on circumstances.
R11: Disruptive cleaning should not be performed in occupied rooms.
R12: The robot appears to be invading the personal space of others. Very few actions are acceptable in that case.
R13: Vacuuming should be limited to unoccupied rooms. Some context is needed with regards to the "starting conversation" option. Assuming the meaning is staying a conversation with the only person visible, the robot needs to face that individual and probably approach closer.
R14: Disruptive cleaning should be limited in occupied rooms.
R15: The robot appears to walk between the TV and people watching the TV. That should be avoided and limits the acceptability of any actions.
R16: Disruptive cleaning should not be performed in occupied rooms.
R17: Disruptive cleaning should be avoided in occupied rooms.
R18: Conversions should be started when facing the recipient. A substantial distance to others is preferable when carrying large objects.
R19: Disruptive actions should be avoided in occupied rooms.
R20: Conversions should be started when facing the recipient in reasonable proximity. Disruptive cleaning should be avoided in occupied rooms.
